{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":38801,"name":"evol","username":"evolgames","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/evolgames/{size}/3169_2.png","created_at":"2020-08-28T04:15:26.457Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003eSetting:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cpre\u003e\u003ccode class=\"lang-auto\"\u003ecamera.zoom = 2\n\u003c/code\u003e\u003c/pre\u003e\n\u003cp\u003edoesn‚Äôt double the zoom, right? And 4 quadruple it and so on? I‚Äôm assuming it doesn‚Äôt work like this.\u003cbr\u003e\nThe camera documentation just says ‚Äúzoom.‚Äù So suppose I set the zoom to 8. How is 8 represented here? Because it doesn‚Äôt appear to be magnifying at each integer. It just looks like you would expect zoom to work in 3d modelling software.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eSo how can I calculate magnification? The application in this case is a sniper scope. I don‚Äôt need realism, just something accurate enough to be believable by the player.\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":1,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2020-08-28T04:15:26.457Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":3,"reads":28,"readers_count":27,"score":20.6,"yours":false,"topic_id":6351,"topic_slug":"how-to-go-about-camera-zoom-magnification","display_username":"evol","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":1292,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":38802,"name":"Eugene Kozlov","username":"Eugene","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/eugene/{size}/902_2.png","created_at":"2020-08-28T07:52:29.490Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003eI‚Äôm not exactly sure what you call ‚Äúmagnification‚Äù.\u003cbr\u003e\nUse FOV if you want to get exact number of degrees.\u003cbr\u003e\nUse zoom if you want to scale up final image (it should work this way, at least).\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":2,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2020-08-28T07:52:29.490Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":28,"readers_count":27,"score":5.6,"yours":false,"topic_id":6351,"topic_slug":"how-to-go-about-camera-zoom-magnification","display_username":"Eugene Kozlov","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"Core developer","title_is_group":false,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":484,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":38803,"name":"evol","username":"evolgames","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/evolgames/{size}/3169_2.png","created_at":"2020-08-28T13:02:49.250Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003eWhat I mean is, I need to zoom my image, but I‚Äôm not sure what the units are for zoom to make sure I‚Äôm at the right magnification.\u003cbr\u003e\nEach scope ‚Äúlevel‚Äù would be a magnification where 2x is twice as ‚Äúzoomed‚Äù as camera.zoom = 1. 4x would be 4 times as zoomed.\u003cbr\u003e\nLike a microscope does, too.\u003cbr\u003e\nIs this something I can calculate or would it be easy to do this via postprocess and effectively double the image in xml?\u003cbr\u003e\n\u003c/p\u003e\u003cdiv class=\"onebox lazyYT lazyYT-container\" data-youtube-id=\"3KRMP_FLm48\" data-youtube-title=\"Scope Zoom Compared at 1 mile, 1,000 and 500 Yards!\" data-parameters=\"feature=oembed\u0026amp;wmode=opaque\"\u003e\n  \u003ca href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3KRMP_FLm48\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener\"\u003e\n    \u003cimg class=\"ytp-thumbnail-image\" src=\"https://i.ytimg.com/vi/3KRMP_FLm48/maxresdefault.jpg\" title=\"Scope Zoom Compared at 1 mile, 1,000 and 500 Yards!\" width=\"690\" height=\"388\"\u003e\n  \u003c/a\u003e\n\u003c/div\u003e\n","post_number":3,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2020-08-28T13:02:49.250Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":26,"readers_count":25,"score":5.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":6351,"topic_slug":"how-to-go-about-camera-zoom-magnification","display_username":"evol","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3KRMP_FLm48","internal":false,"reflection":false,"clicks":0}],"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":1292,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":38804,"name":"È≠îÂ§ßÂÜú ùûçùûéùù≥ ÁèæÊãõËúç","username":"Modanung","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/modanung/{size}/3290_2.png","created_at":"2020-08-28T14:28:51.678Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003eThere is no technical difference between zooming in and reducing the field of view. I‚Äôm not sure what SetZoom does, but my gut memory tells me it is more suitable for 2D. To zoom in using the FOV, simply divide the FOV by the zoom factor. This is how it was done in Unreal Tournament, and it still works today.\u003cbr\u003e\nA second viewport and camera could create a difference between in and out of scope zoom.\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":4,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2020-08-28T14:28:51.678Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":26,"readers_count":25,"score":5.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":6351,"topic_slug":"how-to-go-about-camera-zoom-magnification","display_username":"È≠îÂ§ßÂÜú ùûçùûéùù≥ ÁèæÊãõËúç","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":192,"hidden":false,"trust_level":0,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_suspended":true,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false},{"id":38806,"name":"J Tippetts","username":"JTippetts1","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/jtippetts1/{size}/96_2.png","created_at":"2020-08-28T14:59:34.789Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003eSetZoom() should work the way you expect. Here are some image results from a quick test:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cdiv class=\"lightbox-wrapper\"\u003e\u003ca class=\"lightbox\" href=\"https://global.discourse-cdn.com/standard17/uploads/urho3d/original/2X/4/4f6f082d5c1ade6ddebf9a3c12274bb596af028c.jpeg\" data-download-href=\"/uploads/short-url/bkHBvDu6zmLOcX51OJz12TE1qzi.jpeg?dl=1\" title=\"image\"\u003e\u003cimg src=\"https://global.discourse-cdn.com/standard17/uploads/urho3d/optimized/2X/4/4f6f082d5c1ade6ddebf9a3c12274bb596af028c_2_215x500.jpeg\" alt=\"image\" data-base62-sha1=\"bkHBvDu6zmLOcX51OJz12TE1qzi\" width=\"215\" height=\"500\" srcset=\"https://global.discourse-cdn.com/standard17/uploads/urho3d/optimized/2X/4/4f6f082d5c1ade6ddebf9a3c12274bb596af028c_2_215x500.jpeg, https://global.discourse-cdn.com/standard17/uploads/urho3d/optimized/2X/4/4f6f082d5c1ade6ddebf9a3c12274bb596af028c_2_322x750.jpeg 1.5x, https://global.discourse-cdn.com/standard17/uploads/urho3d/optimized/2X/4/4f6f082d5c1ade6ddebf9a3c12274bb596af028c_2_430x1000.jpeg 2x\" data-small-upload=\"https://global.discourse-cdn.com/standard17/uploads/urho3d/optimized/2X/4/4f6f082d5c1ade6ddebf9a3c12274bb596af028c_2_10x10.png\"\u003e\u003cdiv class=\"meta\"\u003e\u003csvg class=\"fa d-icon d-icon-far-image svg-icon\" aria-hidden=\"true\"\u003e\u003cuse xlink:href=\"#far-image\"\u003e\u003c/use\u003e\u003c/svg\u003e\u003cspan class=\"filename\"\u003eimage\u003c/span\u003e\u003cspan class=\"informations\"\u003e513√ó1193 93.4 KB\u003c/span\u003e\u003csvg class=\"fa d-icon d-icon-discourse-expand svg-icon\" aria-hidden=\"true\"\u003e\u003cuse xlink:href=\"#discourse-expand\"\u003e\u003c/use\u003e\u003c/svg\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/div\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThe top is a render of a scene with a gridded plane at zoom=1. The middle is at zoom=2, and the bottom is at zoom=4. You can see that at each step, the view is of half (vertically) of what the previous zoom step showed.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIf you look at the Camera code, you can see that it uses Frustum to define the projection matrix. Frustum has a \u003ca href=\"https://github.com/urho3d/Urho3D/blob/master/Source/Urho3D/Math/Frustum.cpp#L75\"\u003emethod\u003c/a\u003e that takes the fov, aspect ratio and zoom level to construct the frustum. Inside the body of that method you can see that zoom is used as a divisor of the tangent of the fov, meaning that if you choose zoom levels of 2, 4, 8, etc‚Ä¶ each step halves the size of the near/far planes, meaning a 2x multiplication level.\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":5,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2020-08-28T19:07:11.283Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":26,"readers_count":25,"score":85.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":6351,"topic_slug":"how-to-go-about-camera-zoom-magnification","display_username":"J Tippetts","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":2,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"https://github.com/urho3d/Urho3D/blob/master/Source/Urho3D/Math/Frustum.cpp#L75","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"Urho3D/Frustum.cpp at master ¬∑ urho3d/Urho3D ¬∑ GitHub","clicks":0},{"url":"https://global.discourse-cdn.com/standard17/uploads/urho3d/original/2X/4/4f6f082d5c1ade6ddebf9a3c12274bb596af028c.jpeg","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"4f6f082d5c1ade6ddebf9a3c12274bb596af028c.jpeg","clicks":0}],"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":5}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":631,"hidden":false,"trust_level":0,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":true},{"id":38811,"name":"evol","username":"evolgames","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/evolgames/{size}/3169_2.png","created_at":"2020-08-28T19:08:51.161Z","cooked":"\u003cp\u003eWell that‚Äôs good enough for me!\u003cbr\u003e\nI didn‚Äôt even consider testing it with a grid, that‚Äôs clear as day.\u003c/p\u003e","post_number":6,"post_type":1,"updated_at":"2020-08-28T19:08:51.161Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":5,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":26,"readers_count":25,"score":5.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":6351,"topic_slug":"how-to-go-about-camera-zoom-magnification","display_username":"evol","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"reply_to_user":{"username":"JTippetts1","name":"J Tippetts","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/discourse.urho3d.io/jtippetts1/{size}/96_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,